{{This date in recent years}}
{{Day}}

==Events==
* [[238]] &ndash; [[Year of the Six Emperors]]: The [[Roman Senate]] outlaws emperor [[Maximinus Thrax]] for his bloodthirsty [[proscription]]s in [[Ancient Rome|Rome]] and nominates two of its members, [[Pupienus and Balbinus]], to the throne.
*[[1500]] &ndash; [[Portugal|Portuguese]] [[navigator]] [[Pedro Álvares Cabral]] lands in [[Brazil]].
*[[1519]] &ndash; Spanish [[conquistador]] [[Hernán Cortés]] establishes a settlement at [[Veracruz, Veracruz|Veracruz, Mexico]].
*[[1529]] &ndash; [[Treaty of Saragossa]] divides the eastern hemisphere between [[Spain]] and [[Portugal]] along a line 297.5 leagues or 17° east of the [[Moluccas]].
*[[1622]] &ndash; The [[Capture of Ormuz (1622)|Capture of Ormuz]] by the [[East India Company]] ends Portuguese control of [[Hormuz Island]].
*[[1809]] &ndash; The second day of the [[Battle of Eckmühl]]: the [[Austrian Empire|Austrian]] army is defeated by the [[First French Empire]] army led by [[Napoleon I of France]] and driven over the [[Danube]] in [[Regensburg]].
*[[1836]] &ndash; [[Texas Revolution]]: A day after the [[Battle of San Jacinto]], forces under [[Republic of Texas|Texas]] General [[Sam Houston]] capture [[Mexico|Mexican]] General [[Antonio López de Santa Anna]].
*[[1864]] &ndash; The [[Congress of the United States|U.S. Congress]] passes the [[Coinage Act of 1864]] that mandates that the inscription ''In God We Trust'' be placed on all coins minted as [[United States currency]].
*[[1876]] &ndash; The first ever [[National League]] baseball game is played in [[Philadelphia]].
*[[1889]] &ndash; At high noon, thousands rush to claim land in the [[Land Run of 1889]]. Within hours the cities of [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma|Oklahoma City]] and [[Guthrie, Oklahoma|Guthrie]] are formed with populations of at least 10,000.
*[[1898]] &ndash; [[Spanish-American War]]: The {{USS|Nashville|PG-7|6}} captures a [[Spain|Spanish]] merchant ship.
*[[1906]] &ndash; The [[1906 Summer Olympics]], not now recognized as part of the official [[Olympic Games]], open in [[Athens]].
*[[1911]] &ndash; [[Tsinghua University]], one of [[mainland China]]'s leading universities, is founded.
*[[1912]] &ndash; ''[[Pravda]]'', the "voice" of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]], begins publication in [[Saint Petersburg]].
*[[1915]] &ndash; The use of [[poison gas in World War I]] escalates when [[chlorine|chlorine gas]] is released as a [[Chemical warfare|chemical weapon]] in the [[Second Battle of Ypres]].
*[[1930]] &ndash; The [[United Kingdom]], [[Japan]] and the [[United States]] sign the [[London Naval Treaty]] regulating [[submarine]] warfare and limiting [[shipbuilding]].
*[[1944]] &ndash; The [[1st Air Commando Group]] using [[Sikorsky R-4]] helicopters stage the first use of helicopters in [[military helicopter|combat]] with [[Combat Search and Rescue|CSAR]] operations in the [[China Burma India Theater|China-Burma-India theater]].
*[[1944]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: [[Operation Persecution]] is initiated &ndash; [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] forces land in the [[Jayapura|Hollandia]] (currently known as Jayapura) area of [[New Guinea]].
*[[1945]] &ndash; World War II: Prisoners at the [[Jasenovac concentration camp]] revolt. 520 are killed and 80 escape.
*  1945   &ndash; World War II: [[Führerbunker#Events in 1945|Führerbunker]]: After learning that [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] forces have taken [[Eberswalde]] without a fight, [[Adolf Hitler]] admits defeat in his underground bunker and states that [[suicide]] is his only recourse.
*[[1948]] &ndash; [[1948 Arab-Israeli War]]: [[Haifa]], a major port of [[Israel]], is [[Battle of Haifa (1948)|captured from Arab forces]].
*[[1951]] &ndash; [[Korean War]]: The Chinese [[People's Volunteer Army]] begin assaulting positions defended by the [[Royal Australian Regiment]] and the [[Princess Patricia's Canadian Light Infantry]] at the [[Battle of Kapyong]].
*[[1954]] &ndash; [[Second Red Scare|Red Scare]]: Witnesses begin testifying and live television coverage of the [[Army-McCarthy Hearings]] begins.
*[[1964]] &ndash; The [[1964 New York World's Fair|1964-1965 New York World's Fair]] opens for its first season.
*[[1969]] &ndash; British yachtsman Sir [[Robin Knox-Johnston]] wins the [[Sunday Times Golden Globe Race|''Sunday Times'' Golden Globe Race]] and completes the first solo non-stop circumnavigation of the world.
*[[1970]] &ndash; The first [[Earth Day]] is celebrated.
*[[1972]] &ndash; [[Vietnam War]]: Increased [[United States|American]] bombing in [[Vietnam]] prompts [[Opposition to the Vietnam War|anti-war protests]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City]], and [[San Francisco]].
*[[1977]] &ndash; [[Optical fiber]] is first used to carry live [[telephone]] traffic.
*[[1983]] &ndash; The [[Germany|German]] magazine ''[[Der Stern]]'' claims that the "[[Hitler Diaries]]" had been found in wreckage in [[East Germany]]; the diaries are subsequently revealed to be [[Forgery|forgeries]].
*[[1992]] &ndash; In an [[1992 explosion in Guadalajara|explosion]] in [[Guadalajara]], Mexico, 206 people are killed, nearly 500 injured and 15,000 left homeless.
*[[1993]] &ndash; Version 1.0 of the [[Mosaic (web browser)|Mosaic]] [[web browser]] is released.
*[[1997]] &ndash; [[Haouch Khemisti massacre]] in [[Algeria]] &ndash; 93 villagers killed.
*  1997   &ndash; The [[Japanese embassy hostage crisis]] ends in [[Lima, Peru]].
*[[1998]] &ndash; [[Disney's Animal Kingdom]] opens at [[Walt Disney World]] near [[Orlando, Florida]], [[United States]].
*[[2000]] &ndash; In a pre-dawn raid, federal agents seize six-year-old [[Elián González]] from his relatives' home in [[Miami, Florida]].
*  2000   &ndash; The [[Big Number Change]] takes place in the [[United Kingdom]].
*[[2004]] &ndash; Two fuel trains [[Ryongchon disaster|collide]] in [[Ryongchon]], [[North Korea]], killing up to 150 people.
*[[2005]] &ndash; [[Japan]]'s Prime Minister [[Junichiro Koizumi]] [[List of war apology statements issued by Japan#2000s|apologizes]] for Japan's war record.
*[[2008]] &ndash; The [[United States Air Force]] retires the remaining [[F-117 Nighthawk]] aircraft in service.

